Allows for a new form of document signature.

pkiz_sign will take data and encode it in a string that starts with
the substring  "PKIZ_".  This prefix indicates that the data has been:
1) Signed via PKI in Crypto Message Syntax (CMS) in binary (DER) format
2) Compressed using zlib (comparable to gzip)
3) urlsafe-base64 decoded

This process is reversed to validate the data.

middleware/auth_token.py will be capable of validating Keystone
tokens that are marshalled in the new format.  The current existing
"PKI" tokens will continue to be identified with "MII", issued by
default, and validated as well.  It will require corresponding changes
on the Keystone server to issue the new token format.

A separate script for generating the sample
data used in the unit tests,
examples/pki/gen_cmsz.py,
also serves as an example of how to
call the API from Python code.

stray comma in one of the JSON files made for non-parsing JSON.

Change-Id: Ia9a66ba3742da0bcd58c4c096b28cc8a66ad6569
'}]
commit_message:
Compressed Signature and Validation

Allows for a new form of document signature.

pkiz_sign will take data and encode it in a string that starts with
the substring  "PKIZ_".  This prefix indicates that the data has been:
1) Signed via PKI in Crypto Message Syntax (CMS) in binary (DER) format
2) Compressed using zlib (comparable to gzip)
3) urlsafe-base64 decoded

This process is reversed to validate the data.

middleware/auth_token.py will be capable of validating Keystone
tokens that are marshalled in the new format.  The current existing
"PKI" tokens will continue to be identified with "MII", issued by
default, and validated as well.  It will require corresponding changes
on the Keystone server to issue the new token format.

A separate script for generating the sample
data used in the unit tests,
examples/pki/gen_cmsz.py,
also serves as an example of how to
call the API from Python code.

Some of the sample data for the old tests had to be regenerated. A
stray comma in one of the JSON files made for non-parsing JSON.

Blueprint: compress-tokens
Closes-Bug: #1255321

Change-Id: Ia9a66ba3742da0bcd58c4c096b28cc8a66ad6569

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'files': ['nova/virt/baremetal/ipmi.py'], 'message': "Run ipmi power status less aggressively

Nova bare metal runs IPMI 'power status' in a loop
until the desired state is reach. Running repeated
IPMI commands in a tight loop (1 second sleep) seems
to occasionally cause 'insufficient resources' errors
with some hardware types.

In this commit we update the IPMI retry timer to use
a DynamicLoopingCall which can wait longer for each
retry of the power status command.

Change-Id: Ib933b746607e1fe183204274526ccd34fcacf74c
Closes-bug: #1291991
"}]
commit_message:
Run ipmi power status less aggressively

Nova bare metal runs IPMI 'power status' in a loop
until the desired state is reach. Running repeated
IPMI commands in a tight loop (1 second sleep) seems
to occasionally cause 'insufficient resources' errors
with some hardware types.

In this commit we update the IPMI retry timer to use
a DynamicLoopingCall which can wait longer for each
retry of the power status command.

Change-Id: Ib933b746607e1fe183204274526ccd34fcacf74c
Closes-bug: #1291991

commit_message:
Fix the duplicated extension summaries

If operating `nova --os-compute-api-version 3 extension-list`, the
summaries of both flavor-extra-specs and flavors extensions are the
same "Flavors Extension.". The summary of flavor-extra-specs should
include its feature.
There is a same issue on os-extended-server-attributes and
os-extended-availability-zone extensions also.

This patch fixes these summaries.

Change-Id: I6778229221ca80632b3a303745ff5133488f327d
Related-Bug: #1318973

[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-05-07 14:28:42.000000000', 'files': ['muranoapi/openstack/common/log.py', 'muranoapi/tests/test_log.py'], 'message': 'Fixed python2.6 compat for RFCSysLogHandler

(From the original bug report):
Currently used pattern in RFCSysLogHandler will fail for Python
2.6.x (using super(RFCSysLogHandler, self)).
In order to fix the broken Python 2.6.x compatibility, old style
explicit superclass method calls should be used instead.

Uses e.g. logging.handlers.SysLogHandler.__init__(self,...)
rather than super(RFCSysLogHandler, self).__init__(...)

Change-Id: Ia81e00e4a7763a887703d0ef83e475f314eab28d
Closes-Bug: #1306559
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed python2.6 compat for RFCSysLogHandler

(From the original bug report):
Currently used pattern in RFCSysLogHandler will fail for Python
2.6.x (using super(RFCSysLogHandler, self)).
In order to fix the broken Python 2.6.x compatibility, old style
explicit superclass method calls should be used instead.

Uses e.g. logging.handlers.SysLogHandler.__init__(self,...)
rather than super(RFCSysLogHandler, self).__init__(...)

Change-Id: Ia81e00e4a7763a887703d0ef83e475f314eab28d
Closes-Bug: #1306559

commit_message:
Add service validation and encapsulation

This patch moves the keystone service resource
to a new class, keystone::service, and adds
a new resource that uses the admin credentials
to confirm the keystone server is accepting
connections and functioning well from the client
perspective. This validation resource is optional
and if specified will be required by all keystone
custom types.

In order to take advantage of this change, consumers
of the keystone service should depend on this class
instead of the keystone service.

Change-Id: Ibd92a7c40658bb242b3b55980489949cb5835145

commit_message:
Fix bug with cleanup running for locked tests

Code for lock aquiring modified.

- locks are aquired inside try statement,
 prevents from being interrupted outside of main flow
- prevent 500 error in case process was already stopped
- remove SIGUSR1 interrupt handler with SIG_DFL
 which simply returns 0

Change-Id: Icc31510db705b11c2b628604d0480d8da6aedeca
Closes-Bug: #1318631

ml2: gre, vxlan type driver can leak segment_id

When multiple region of segment_id is specified, segment_id can leak
(will be never reused) on deletion of network.

commit_message:
On Python <= 2.6, use simplejson if available

Until Python 2.7, stdlib json module was not boosted with a C extension,
meaning bad performance. Try to use simplejson module if available.

RHEL 6.5 is one of the platforms that still ship Python 2.6.

The original idea of the patch belongs to Miguel Angel Ajo Pelayo @
mangelajo@redhat.com

Change-Id: Ib3dc0b713ed90396919feba018772243b3b9c90f
Closes-Bug: 1314129

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-05-01 15:21:12.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/test/test_data/exceptions.py'], 'message': 'Fix fake_init_exception() to better handle Neutron exceptions

Neutron often declares exceptions by overriding the message attribute
and possibly adding additional information later, like a 'reason' for
the failure, rather than passing the code and message around as
arguments.  We should handle this appropriately and display the correct
message, instead of failing with "TypeError: fake_init_exception()
takes exactly 3 arguments (1 given)"

Change-Id: Ib838704cb9ca968ddfc6e3bfed3af7d0ea08f384
Closes-Bug: #1315035
'}]
commit_message:
Fix fake_init_exception() to better handle Neutron exceptions

Neutron often declares exceptions by overriding the message attribute
and possibly adding additional information later, like a 'reason' for
the failure, rather than passing the code and message around as
arguments.  We should handle this appropriately and display the correct
message, instead of failing with "TypeError: fake_init_exception()
takes exactly 3 arguments (1 given)"

Change-Id: Ib838704cb9ca968ddfc6e3bfed3af7d0ea08f384
Closes-Bug: #1315035

commit_message:
Enable plots with no successful iterations

The stacked and pie graphs can still be produced when there are no
successful iterations. The pie chart ilustrates this well by showing 100%
error. However the histogram cannot be produced as the number of bins
cannot be calculated, so this is skipped.

Also hides atomic actions header and select when there are no atomic
actions results.

closes-bug: #1315063
Change-Id: Ic1fb7f00550828a8e374a94034c1b8eb07db5e89

commit_message:
Use safe way through "with" statement to work with files

It's unsafe to just open and write to file. Cause if something went wrong
during writing to file we won't close fd.

Change-Id: I924b8962b3e0c936f3a20260844178783feaf544

commit_message:
add support for FreeIPA backend - phase 1

This commit adds support for using FreeIPA as the DNS
backend.  This implementation uses the FreeIPA JSON
interface, doing HTTPS for security and Kerberos for
authentication.  The requirements are:
* python-kerberos 1.1 or later
* MIT kerberos5 version 1.11.3 or later
* A FreeIPA deployment, with an account that has access
to manage the DNS portion.  The admin@DOMAIN account
can be used for testing, but is not recommended for
production.  You must generate a keytab for this account
and Designate Central must have read access to
the keytab file.
* The CA cert file from FreeIPA (default /etc/ipa/ca.crt).

Specify backend_driver = ipa in the service:central config to
use the ipa backend.

The configuration parameters in the backend:ipa section are:
ipa_host - The hostname of the FreeIPA server (FQDN, for Kerberos)
ipa_port - default 443 - port number for web services listener
ipa_client_keytab - Kerberos client keytab file
ipa_ca_cert - HTTPS client CA certificate file
ipa_base_url - Base URL of web services server
             - default https://$ipa_host/ipa
ipa_json_url - IPA JSON RPC server
             - default $ipa_base_url/json
ipa_connect_retries - default 1 - the kerberos credentials will
expire periodically - the ipa backend will detect this and reauth
    - ipa will attempt to retry the auth this many times before giving
      up with an exception
ipa_force_ns_use - default False - IPA will attempt to resolve any
    server specified in an SOA mname or NS record - setting this parameter
    to True will force IPA to accept servers that cannot be resolved
ipa_version - version of IPA RPC - default 2.65
ipa_auth_driver_class - this is the domain + class name of the authentication
    driver (subclass of requests.auth.AuthBase) that the ipa backend will use
    to perform authentication against IPA
    - default designate.backend.impl_ipa.auth.IPAAuth
Implements: blueprint ipa-backend
Change-Id: I798ab4d7ff0df76e04825febe5ea33690050fa05

commit_message:
Make the LDAP debug option a configurable setting

The LDAP OPT_DEBUG_LEVEL is very useful for debugging LDAP
problems with Keystone. This change makes it easier to set
and find. The default will be to have it disabled.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I342fe2eea752bd8632074600386f0173e7328132

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-05-06 10:57:01.000000000', 'files': ['neutron/api/v2/base.py', 'neutron/tests/unit/test_policy.py', 'neutron/policy.py', 'etc/policy.json', 'neutron/common/exceptions.py'], 'message': "Perform policy checks only once on list responses

The policy engine is currently being called for every attribute
of every resource to be returned by a list response. This is
harming the API performance; moreover such a high number of checks
is also unnecessary.

This patch therefore slightly changes the API logic so that list
response first determine the list of attributes which should be
returned querying the policy engine and then use this list for
all resource items to be returned.

To this aim a few methods in base.py needed to be refactored.
This patch also removes the routine check_if_exists from policy.py
and the related PolicyNotFound exception.

Finally, this patch also removes unnecessary admin_or_owner rules
when applied to attributes. This kind of rule indeed has no effect
anyway because of Neutron's ownership checks. The rules were removed
because this change won't allow anymore for having attribute-level
policies whose evaluation result depends on the resource value.

Implements blueprint faster-list-responses

Change-Id: I21b8273add5d5984f512ad94af5a99cf0b0a5d93
"}]
commit_message:
Perform policy checks only once on list responses

The policy engine is currently being called for every attribute
of every resource to be returned by a list response. This is
harming the API performance; moreover such a high number of checks
is also unnecessary.

This patch therefore slightly changes the API logic so that list
response first determine the list of attributes which should be
returned querying the policy engine and then use this list for
all resource items to be returned.

To this aim a few methods in base.py needed to be refactored.
This patch also removes the routine check_if_exists from policy.py
and the related PolicyNotFound exception.

Finally, this patch also removes unnecessary admin_or_owner rules
when applied to attributes. This kind of rule indeed has no effect
anyway because of Neutron's ownership checks. The rules were removed
because this change won't allow anymore for having attribute-level
policies whose evaluation result depends on the resource value.

Implements blueprint faster-list-responses

Change-Id: I21b8273add5d5984f512ad94af5a99cf0b0a5d93

commit_message:
Adds SecretMetadatum table

This patch is the first planned in a series to add KMIP support to Barbican.
Barbican currently returns metadata about secrets to the user, but adding
secret_metadata table will allow users to set additional metadata options
that are not supported by Barbican.

After this submission is accepted, another patch will be created to move the
current Secret attribute metadata to the new metadata table.

Change-Id: Ibc990f798b118eeda705360e40ecf439d5a1b0cd
Implements: blueprint add-metadata-to-secrets

Docker containers have only "eth0" and "lo" interfaces by default.
So if we deploy fuel on any non "eth0" interface, then
/etc/dnsmasq.conf file will have worng "interface" parameter which

'}]
commit_message:
Use eth0 as dhcp_interface in cobbler container

Docker containers have only "eth0" and "lo" interfaces by default.
So if we deploy fuel on any non "eth0" interface, then
/etc/dnsmasq.conf file will have worng "interface" parameter which
breaks DHCP discovery. We need to hardcode dhcp_interface=eth0.

Change-Id: Iae32f1139fffca1cb77484978d07631ceed4fcee
Closes-bug: #1319412

commit_message:
Use HTTP exceptions from oslo

glanceclient currently keeps its own set of HTTP exceptions in exc.py. This is
duplicative of definitions provided in oslo's apiclient/exceptions.py. This file
is already synced, so it is just a matter of using it. exc.py will hold the few
remaining exceptions that are not provided elsewhere. test_exc is removed since
oslo's unit tests are more complete.

Change-Id: I4c5a496f2b43e89d3a13919b2456c4d82d617075

commit_message:
Upgrade failure for DB2 at ml2_binding_vif_details

50d5ba354c23_ml2_binding_vif_details fails during upgrade
when DB2 is used as the DB backend of neutron because
Boolean type is not supported by DB2.

This fix uses "1" instead of "true" in sql when db2 is engine.
This fix also changes context creation to op.execute.

Change-Id: I82d2141007894342c634f2c5e62344e20d876d8f
Closes-Bug: 1311589

[{'number': 12, 'created': '2014-05-10 09:21:00.000000000', 'files': ['contrib/lp-cedarish/docker/build-app'], 'message': 'Docker Build-Script Enhancements

commit_message:
Docker Build-Script Enhancements

- Speeds up build times for ghost by 2X.
- Allows caching of git repos.
- Allows reusing images if repo is unchanged
- Git dir name is now a hash of the git URL.
- Added an elapsed time indication in build log.
- Simplified the image id fetch to use awk.
- Eliminated the redundant echo at the end.
- Corrected bug in previous patchset that gets an
incorrect image id from glance.

Build times taking 5 minutes before are now
completing in 160 sec. Allows caching the git
repo and will git pull if there is a previous one
present. If the git pull is up-to-date, then a
new image is not built, and the previous one
is used. This can be changed by setting the
REUSE_IMAGES_IF_REPO_UNCHANGED environment variable
to 0 to cause a rebuild even when the repo is
unchanged since the last build.

Enhances the Docker build script so that it keeps
timestamped log files. The log file location can
be controlled by setting the SOLUM_BUILD_LOG
environment variable.

Change-Id: Ie5523d81a49bb4d94291f35091435819b3bc5a05

commit_message:
search for duplicated ”provided” elements

An image should only have a single operating-system,
for example an image cannot be both fedora and ubuntu.
Verify prior to building the image that the user has not
specified more than one.

With this change, additional elements can still provide
root.d files.

Unlike the previous patchset, the change is done directly
in element_dependencies.py and generalized to any kind of
“provided” elements.

Change-Id: Ib536e372a3768f8b97aaec902a4426636adf7c37

Convert SolidFire Capacity response to GiB

This patch fixes the reported free_capacity_gb response
in the SolidFire update_cluster_status method.

The initial patch fixed the free_capacity conversion,
however omitted the same fix that was needed for the
free_space calculation.

Closes Bug: #1284452

commit_message:
Remove dib git refs from the disk images.

This element removes dib git references from the disk images as a
cleanup operation, walking /etc/dib-source-repositories to identify
and remove associated .git structures, it, dib-manifests and
dib-pip-manifests, for installations where static point in time,
images are used and nothing but from seed forklift image upgrades
are preferred.

Change-Id: I2f68fb2f38b223e3a50ef9e1767ed2d2c01354be

commit_message:
Add IPv4 flag for Ironic's TFTP setup

TFTP binds to the IPv6 interface by default on Fedora, and as a result
some machines may fail PXE booting. Adding the IPv4 flag makes the TFTP
server bind to IPv4 consistently.

Change-Id: I0fdacb0d91eece8cdc52d7bc7cc76a28efaf3751
Closes-Bug: #1306554

commit_message:
Add HEAT_UNDERCLOUD_EXTRA_OPTS back

Change I8ff50ca092e1209167cd9818b680f56a7512bba3 inadvertently
removed the adding of the extra options to the heat command to
set the power user data correctly.

I find it very troubling that this was not caught in CI.

Closes-bug: 1318750
Change-Id: I48ede36ae97142085e830fb4e8e7a31697c96c6b
